Another great TED talk, this time by Sunni Brown.

Karl recently cited this PNAS article in his blog post about the link between environment and society. I started reading it but could not get past the third sentence in the abstract; just those three sentences gave me plenty to think about.

Sentence 1: &rdquo;&hellip;the human condition is tightly linked to environmental condition.&rdquo;
I absolutely agree! E.g. The Forsaken Garden by Nancy Ryley - I just started reading this book, about a CBC documentary filmmaker who got struck with &ldquo;environmental illness&rdquo; in the 70&rsquo;s at the height of her career.

Doing research in Churchill is not without its perils: sleep deprivation, bugs, road rage, and polar bears. Brittany said it was a slow season so far, but not every bear read the memo: see this CBC article on a polar bear gone wild.&nbsp;
All joking aside, sadly enough when wildlife goes wild, the consequences for the animal in question are much more severe than an&nbsp;embarrassing Youtube video.
From the original CBC article: notice the person behind the rock, a little to the left of the hind legs!

Last year, I wrote a couple of posts about the importance of natural history in science:
http://www.cottenielab.org/2010/04/hypotheses-or-data-first.htmlhttp://www.cottenielab.org/2010/04/hypotheses-or-data-first-update.htmlhttp://www.cottenielab.org/2010/04/hypotheses-or-data-first-update-2.htmlI argued that natural history forms the basis of the scientific method, but I also acknowledged that the power of the scientific method came from the interaction between data and hypotheses, yadayada.&nbsp;
However, one important thing that I forgot to add in that discussion is that natural history does not only form the basis of the scientific method, but also the basis of our interest in science.

